
This is the final stage where NAMS (Nutrition Assessment Management System) goes from a development project to a live clinical tool used across your Sahakar Smart Clinic outlets.
1. Production Deployment (The "Launch")
We will use Vercel for hosting because it is optimized for Next.js and offers high performance in India.
Step 1: Database Provisioning:
Initialize the production PostgreSQL database (Vercel Postgres or Supabase).
Run npx prisma db push to create the tables in the live environment.
Step 2: Environment Variables:
Configure the production .env in the Vercel Dashboard (DATABASE_URL, NEXTAUTH_SECRET, APP_URL).
Step 3: Custom Domain:
Connect your professional domain (e.g., nams.sahakarclinic.com).
Vercel automatically provisions an SSL certificate (HTTPS) for medical data security.
Step 4: The Final Migration:
Run the Migration Script one last time to pull the very latest data from your Google Sheets so the system starts with 100% up-to-date history.
2. Admin Onboarding (The "Setup")
Before the nutritionists log in, the Admin must configure the system's "Brain."
Outlet Configuration: Admin logs in and adds the 5+ Sahakar Smart Clinic locations (Makkaraparamba, Manjeri, etc.).
Test Master List: Admin categorizes the tests (e.g., Blood, Vitamins, Liver) to ensure the nutritionist sees an organized form.
Nutritionist Accounts: Admin creates the initial login credentials for the staff at each outlet.
3. Nutritionist Onboarding (The "Training")
The goal is to show the nutritionists how NAMS makes their life easier compared to Google Forms.
The "Speed" Training (30 Mins):
The Lookup Advantage: Show how typing a phone number (e.g., 9633435228 for Deepa) brings up her whole history instantly.
The BMI Cheat-Sheet: Show how the app calculates the BMI automatically, removing the need for a calculator.
The Tabbed Form: Show how to quickly find tests like "HBA1C" or "Lipid Profile" within their categories.
Device Setup:
Help nutritionists "Add to Home Screen" on their tablets or mobile phones so NAMS looks and feels like a native app.
Ensure browser auto-fill is disabled for clinical fields to prevent data entry errors.
4. Post-Launch Hyper-Care (Week 1-2)
In the first two weeks of NAMS being live:
Daily Sync: A 5-minute check-in to see if any medical tests are missing from the Master List.
Data Audit: Admin checks the first 50 entries to ensure BMI and Outlet tagging are 100% correct.
The "Legacy" Cleanup: If any old patient data was imported with errors (e.g., misspelled names in Google Sheets), the nutritionist uses the "Edit Patient" feature to fix it.
5. Growth & Scaling (Future Proofing)
As Sahakar Smart Clinic adds more outlets:
Outlet Expansion: Adding "Outlet 6" or "Outlet 10" takes exactly 10 seconds in the Admin panel.
New Services: If you add a new test like "Food Allergy Panel," the Admin adds it to the Master List, and it is instantly available at all 10 outlets.
Analytics: Every 3 months, the Admin can export a "Full Master Report" to see which clinic is doing the most assessments and which patients (by BMI category) are most frequent.
Final Project Summary:
PRD: Defined the business problem and the "Smart Clinic" solution.
Architecture: Built a scalable Next.js + PostgreSQL foundation.
UI/UX: Designed a 4-step stepper to end "Form Fatigue."
Migration: Built a bridge to save your historical Google Sheets data.
QA: Ensured clinical accuracy of BMI and test results.
Launch: Professional deployment on Vercel with role-based access.
NAMS is now ready for development.
